info.description: An attacker might target this system to gain unauthorized access to sensitive data stored in the cloud, leveraging the infrastructure and resources for malicious purposes.
An attacker exploits weak access controls by guessing or cracking passwords of users or administrators, allowing unauthorized access to sensitive data.
Identify the target system or application that has weak access controls to focus the attack efforts.
Collect or guess usernames of users or administrators of the target system.
Use techniques such as brute force or password spraying to guess or crack the passwords.
Use the obtained credentials to log into the system and gain unauthorized access to sensitive data.
The attacker could perform a man-in-the-middle attack to intercept data transmitted over the network between users and the cloud services, gaining access to sensitive information.
The attacker gains access to the network where data transmissions occur.
The attacker deploys tools capable of intercepting and capturing the network traffic.
The attacker captures data transmitted over the network.
The attacker extracts sensitive information from the captured data.
Through phishing attacks targeting administrators, the attacker could obtain credentials to access the cloud management interface and sensitive data.
The attacker crafts a deceptive email designed to appear as though it is from a trusted source, targeting administrators specifically.
The attacker sends the crafted phishing email to the targeted administrators, aiming to trick them into revealing their login credentials.
The attacker captures the credentials entered by the administrators who fall for the phishing email.
Using the obtained credentials, the attacker logs into the cloud management interface, gaining unauthorized access to sensitive data and systems.
An attacker finds and exploits vulnerabilities in the Smart Cloud API, gaining unauthorized access to perform actions on resources or extract sensitive data.
The attacker scans the Smart Cloud API to identify any security weaknesses or vulnerabilities that can be exploited.
Based on the identified vulnerabilities, the attacker develops or acquires tools to exploit the weaknesses.
The attacker uses the developed tools to exploit the vulnerabilities, gaining unauthorized access to the API.
With access, the attacker performs unauthorized actions such as data theft or manipulation of cloud resources.
By injecting malware into VM images, an attacker could gain control when these images are used to create new VMs, accessing any data processed by those VMs.
Find a vulnerability in the VM image repository that can be exploited to inject malware.
Inject malware into the VM image while it is stored in the vulnerable repository.
Monitor the deployment of VMs using the tampered images to ensure the malware activates correctly.
An attacker might target this system to disrupt cloud services, affecting availability and reliability for users and businesses.
An attacker launches a Distributed Denial of Service (DDoS) attack targeting the cloud infrastructure, overwhelming the network and servers to disrupt service availability.

The attacker needs to gain control of a botnet, which consists of a network of compromised computers or IoT devices. This step is essential to have the necessary resources to generate a large volume of traffic.

The attacker identifies the specific servers or resources in the cloud infrastructure that will be the focus of the DDoS attack. This involves scouting for vulnerabilities or network architecture details.
The attacker uses the controlled botnet to send a massive amount of traffic to the targeted servers. This step is executed to overwhelm the network and disrupt the service availability.
An attacker exploits inadequate network segmentation to access and disrupt multiple components of the cloud infrastructure, leading to widespread service disruption.
The attacker gains initial access to the network through phishing, exploiting weak credentials, or other entry tactics.
Once inside the network, the attacker explores network configurations and identifies weaknesses in network segmentation.
The attacker exploits these segmentation flaws to move laterally across network segments without proper security controls.
With lateral movement, the attacker accesses critical systems and data that should have been isolated.
The attacker deploys malware or other disruptive tools to multiple components of the infrastructure.
Leveraging access from compromised systems, the attacker disrupts services leading to widespread service disruption.
An attacker exploits known vulnerabilities in the virtual machines used by the cloud service to cause a disruption in cloud operations and services.
Locate and identify virtual machines with known security vulnerabilities suitable for exploitation.
Develop or acquire exploit code tailored to target the identified vulnerabilities in the virtual machines.
Execute the exploit against the targeted virtual machines to gain unauthorized access or disrupt services.
Use the initial foothold to expand control within the cloud environment, targeting additional resources or data.

By compromising administrator credentials, an attacker gains unauthorized access to the cloud management platform, thereby being able to manipulate configurations, disrupt services or allocate resources improperly.
Identify the administrator whose credentials are to be compromised. This involves collecting information about the network and its users.
Launch a phishing campaign aimed at the identified administrator to deceive them into revealing their credentials through a fraudulent website or email.
Alternatively, install a keylogger malware on the administrator's device to capture credentials directly as they are typed.
Use the obtained credentials to log into the cloud management platform and gain unauthorized access to perform malicious activities.

An attacker might target this system to exploit its scalable infrastructure, enabling the deployment of malicious applications or services that can grow without limits, furthering their reach and impact.

An attacker uses stolen credentials to access the cloud platform and deploys a virtual machine that hosts malicious applications. This VM can scale automatically, spreading harmful activities across the infrastructure.
The attacker acquires stolen credentials needed to access the cloud platform.
Using the stolen credentials, the attacker gains unauthorized access to the cloud platform.
The attacker deploys a compromised or malicious virtual machine to execute harmful activities within the cloud environment.
The virtual machine is configured to scale automatically, spreading the malicious applications across multiple infrastructure components.

Through the exploitation of an application deployment pipeline on the cloud platform, an attacker injects malicious code into legitimate applications. As the application scales, the malicious code distributes widely.
The attacker identifies a vulnerability or weak spot in the application deployment pipeline, which can be exploited to inject malicious code.
The attacker exploits the identified vulnerability to inject malicious code into the application deployment process.
The attacker monitors the propagation of the code to ensure it spreads widely as the application scales.
An attacker initiates a resource exhaustion attack by excessively scaling applications or services, leading to denial of service (DoS) for legitimate users and processes.
The attacker identifies a critical resource such as CPU, memory, or network bandwidth that can be targeted to exhaust.
The attacker initiates processes or applications that consume an excessive amount of the targeted resource, creating high load and dysfunction.
The attacker monitors the availability and performance of the service while adjusting the attack methods to maximize impact.
As the resource becomes exhausted and services begin to fail, the attacker takes advantage to disrupt further or gain unauthorized access.
An attacker might target this system to manipulate resource allocation, potentially hoarding or misallocating resources to disrupt service for legitimate users and compromise system performance.
An attacker exploits weak identity and access management policies to gain unauthorized access to the cloud management interface, allowing them to manipulate resource allocation.
The attacker scans for weak or misconfigured IAM policies that could be exploited.
Using the identified vulnerabilities, the attacker exploits these weak policies to gain unauthorized access.
The attacker uses their unauthorized access to log into the cloud management interface.
Utilizing vulnerabilities in the virtualization software, an attacker performs VM hopping to gain control over other virtual machines and misallocate their resources.
The attacker identifies vulnerabilities in the virtualization software, which are potential points for exploitation.
Using the identified vulnerabilities, the attacker exploits the system to gain unauthorized access to a virtual machine.
After accessing a vulnerable virtual machine, the attacker elevates their privileges to gain full control over it.
The attacker uses the controlled virtual machine as a base to launch attacks on other virtual machines in the same network.
The attacker misallocates the resources of other virtual machines, leading to performance degradation or denial of service.
By abusing exposed APIs, an attacker programmatically creates excessive virtual machines or storage blocks, consuming available resources disproportionately and impacting service availability.
The attacker scans for exposed or poorly secured APIs that can be leveraged to conduct the attack.
Using found vulnerabilities or inadequate security measures, the attacker sends numerous requests to create virtual machines or storage blocks.
The attacker monitors the success of the attack, verifying that resource consumption is degrading service availability.
An insider with administrative access deliberately misconfigures resource allocation to either hoard resources or misallocate them, leading to reduced service quality or denial of service.
The insider obtains administrative privileges, either through their role or by exploiting system vulnerabilities.
Using their administrative access, the insider intentionally misconfigures resource settings to hoard or misallocate resources.
An attacker might target this system to bypass robust security measures and compliance standards to access and exploit protected data, undermining the system's integrity and regulatory compliance.

An attacker could exploit flaws in the identity and access management controls to gain unauthorized access to restricted areas of the Smart Cloud platform. This compromises both the system's integrity and compliance with security standards.
The attacker identifies vulnerabilities in the access control mechanisms of the Smart Cloud platform.
The attacker exploits these vulnerabilities to bypass security measures and gain unauthorized access to restricted areas.
Once access is gained, the attacker employs various techniques to maintain access and avoid detection.
The attacker extracts sensitive data from the platform which can be used for further attacks or sold for profit.

By targeting the data transmission between components, an attacker might capture or alter sensitive data in transit. Using techniques such as Man-in-the-Middle attacks could undermine the encryption and network segmentation protections.
The attacker identifies the network over which the data transmission occurs, including understanding the security measures in place.
The attacker captures data transmitted over the network possibly using methods like packet sniffing or Man-in-the-Middle attacks to intercept and possibly alter the transmitted data.

Inserting malicious code into the Smart Cloud's operational software or during the API interaction that could lead to unauthorized operations and data breaches, effectively bypassing standard security protocols.
The attacker identifies a vulnerability in the Smart Cloud's software or API that can be exploited.
The attacker develops or acquires malicious code tailored to exploit the identified vulnerability.
The attacker deploys the malicious code through the software or API, initiating unauthorized operations or data access.

By stealing credentials of an Administrator user or escalating normal user privileges, attackers can gain full control over the Smart Cloud platform, allowing them to bypass security measures silently and undetected.
The attacker gathers credentials of an administrator through techniques such as phishing, social engineering, or exploiting software vulnerabilities.
Using the obtained credentials, the attacker escalates a normal user's privileges to that of an administrator by exploiting system vulnerabilities or configuration errors.
Now with admin privileges, the attacker performs unauthorized actions such as tampering with system settings, accessing confidential data, or altering security measures.
